  <static seed="67" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions20.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{3}{7} + \frac{1}{9}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{34}{63}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>7</m> and <m>9</m> is <m>63</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{\frac{3}{7}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>63</m>, we multiply <m>9</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{3}{7} \amp = \frac{3 \cdot 9}{7 \cdot 9}\\ \amp = \frac{27}{63}\end{aligned} }</m></p>
<p>Similarly, we change the second fraction<rsq/>s denominator to <m>63</m>:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{1}{9} \amp = \frac{1 \cdot 7}{9 \cdot 7}\\ \amp = \frac{7}{63} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Now we can add those two fractions. The full process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{3}{7} + \frac{1}{9}
        \amp = \frac{27}{63} + \frac{7}{63} \\
        \amp = \frac{27 + 7}{63} \\
        \amp = \frac{34}{63}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer is  <m>\displaystyle{\frac{34}{63}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
